<body region="r1">
<div>
<p begin="00:00:02.889" end="00:00:10.680" style="s2">Today we will finish Freud.</p>
<p begin="00:00:10.680" end="00:00:21.560" style="s2"> Freud has a peculiar position in the history of psychology, because Freud</p>
<p begin="00:00:21.560" end="00:00:24.249" style="s2"> was not a psychologist, but a doctor.</p>
<p begin="00:00:24.249" end="00:00:30.869" style="s2"> Many of the clinicians whose theories we discuss were doctors,</p>
<p begin="00:00:30.869" end="00:00:31.869" style="s2"> no psychologists.</p>
<p begin="00:00:31.869" end="00:00:37.120" style="s2"> In Freud&#39;s time, during his training, psychology was nonexistent</p>
<p begin="00:00:37.120" end="00:00:38.890" style="s2"> independent science.</p>
<p begin="00:00:38.890" end="00:00:43.950" style="s2"> The same goes for Jung. As a result,</p>
<p begin="00:00:43.950" end="00:00:50.329" style="s2"> that as the new science of psychology evolved into what you are studying now, the psychoanalysts</p>
<p begin="00:00:50.329" end="00:00:53.239" style="s2"> and the medical world, were not involved.</p>
<p begin="00:00:53.239" end="00:00:59.800" style="s2"> There has never been a meeting between the ideas of the experimental psychologists</p>
<p begin="00:00:59.800" end="00:01:00.969" style="s2"> and the psychoanalysts.</p>
<p begin="00:01:00.969" end="00:01:09.189" style="s2"> Although in the 1980s cognitive psychologists proclaimed their discovery of the cognitive unconscious,</p>
<p begin="00:01:09.189" end="00:01:14.990" style="s2"> which made me somewhat ungrateful, since Freud, in fact</p>
<p begin="00:01:14.990" end="00:01:20.390" style="s2"> had laid the foundations for the theory of the unconscious, and that quite extensively</p>
<p begin="00:01:20.390" end="00:01:23.610" style="s2"> almost a hundred years earlier.</p>
<p begin="00:01:23.610" end="00:01:32.260" style="s2"> There is some resistance, as a psychoanalyst would say, among experimental psychologists,</p>
<p begin="00:01:32.260" end="00:01:36.140" style="s2"> to give Freud recognition for his discoveries. And I think that</p>
<p begin="00:01:36.140" end="00:01:43.000" style="s2"> is very unhappy because 1) he made the discoveries, and 2) the psychoanalysts</p>
<p begin="00:01:43.010" end="00:01:48.220" style="s2"> still have more insight into the nature of the unconscious than modern experimental psychologists.</p>
<p begin="00:01:48.220" end="00:01:54.280" style="s2"> Because modern experimental psychologists are convinced that the brain is a cognitive device,</p>
<p begin="00:01:54.280" end="00:01:58.340" style="s2"> something like a computer, and they are not.</p>
<p begin="00:01:58.340" end="00:02:03.200" style="s2"> It is a living system composed of other living subsystems.</p>
<p begin="00:02:03.200" end="00:02:11.060" style="s2"> That means, as we have already discussed, that is the human psyche and its components</p>
<p begin="00:02:11.060" end="00:02:17.400" style="s2"> better regarded as personalities and sub-personalities, than in any other way,</p>
<p begin="00:02:17.400" end="00:02:22.670" style="s2"> such as systems or information processing mechanisms.</p>
<p begin="00:02:22.670" end="00:02:24.040" style="s2"></p>
<p begin="00:02:24.040" end="00:02:32.120" style="s2"> I think it is the most fundamental achievement of psychoanalysis, in the footsteps of Nietzsche,</p>
<p begin="00:02:32.120" end="00:02:40.650" style="s2"> to think of the human mind, the psyche, as a collection of relatively integrated sub-personalities.</p>
<p begin="00:02:40.650" end="00:02:47.720" style="s2"> Even when modern people talk about themselves, they talk about the &quot;me,&quot;</p>
<p begin="00:02:47.720" end="00:02:52.379" style="s2"> which is roughly the Freudian ego. They tend to see themselves as a unit.</p>
<p begin="00:02:52.379" end="00:02:54.409" style="s2"></p>
<p begin="00:02:54.409" end="00:03:01.440" style="s2"> The problem with that idea is that people are constantly doing things ... they are doing things</p>
<p begin="00:03:01.440" end="00:03:05.370" style="s2"> they don&#39;t actually want to do, things they&#39;re ashamed of,</p>
<p begin="00:03:05.370" end="00:03:09.500" style="s2"> lie if they don&#39;t want to lie, or misbehave in general.</p>
<p begin="00:03:09.500" end="00:03:14.110" style="s2"> And everyone knows you can try to be yourself</p>
<p begin="00:03:14.110" end="00:03:17.220" style="s2"> to command something, but that doesn&#39;t really work.</p>
<p begin="00:03:17.220" end="00:03:21.670" style="s2"> You have undoubtedly experienced this many times in your own life.</p>
<p begin="00:03:21.670" end="00:03:25.070" style="s2"> If you&#39;re trying to study for something, you&#39;re not really</p>
<p begin="00:03:25.070" end="00:03:31.290" style="s2"> interested in, all kinds of alternative options will appear</p>
<p begin="00:03:31.290" end="00:03:35.189" style="s2"> in the theater of your imagination.</p>
<p begin="00:03:35.189" end="00:03:44.290" style="s2"> What happens in such situations is that parts of you are organized</p>
<p begin="00:03:44.290" end="00:03:52.349" style="s2"> for other purposes, or from the Freudian perspective, being driven by other desires,</p>
<p begin="00:03:52.349" end="00:03:55.409" style="s2"> trying to hijack your motor systems.</p>
<p begin="00:03:55.409" end="00:04:04.160" style="s2"> That happens regularly, you postpone things</p>
<p begin="00:04:04.160" end="00:04:09.090" style="s2"> whether you rationalize or shift, those are all Freudian concepts.</p>
<p begin="00:04:09.090" end="00:04:13.140" style="s2"> Shift is, for example, that instead of doing what you have to do,</p>
<p begin="00:04:13.140" end="00:04:14.140" style="s2"> is going to do something else.</p>
<p begin="00:04:14.140" end="00:04:20.180" style="s2"> That&#39;s not a bad way to procrastinate, but it&#39;s also not great because you</p>
<p begin="00:04:20.180" end="00:04:22.100" style="s2"> don&#39;t focus on what to focus on.</p>
<p begin="00:04:22.100" end="00:04:25.990" style="s2"> In a way, you are at war with myself.</p>
<p begin="00:04:25.990" end="00:04:30.980" style="s2"> And the main player in the war, at least in principle, is the ego.</p>
<p begin="00:04:30.980" end="00:04:35.500" style="s2"> That is the conscious mind, at least in the early stages of its theory formation.</p>
<p begin="00:04:35.500" end="00:04:38.800" style="s2"> It&#39;s complicated to talk about Freud because his theory evolved</p>
<p begin="00:04:38.800" end="00:04:44.220" style="s2"> in the course of time. In the beginning, he divided the mind into the conscious mind</p>
<p begin="00:04:44.220" end="00:04:46.040" style="s2"> and the unconscious mind.</p>
<p begin="00:04:46.040" end="00:04:50.530" style="s2"> You can see the conscious mind as yourself, the self</p>
<p begin="00:04:50.530" end="00:04:54.090" style="s2"> that you can refer to in your everyday experience.</p>
<p begin="00:04:54.090" end="00:05:01.340" style="s2"> And the unconscious mind is a storehouse for two kinds of phenomena.</p>
<p begin="00:05:01.340" end="00:05:10.200" style="s2"> Drives, which are anchored in instincts, and can conflict with</p>
<p begin="00:05:10.200" end="00:05:17.890" style="s2"> your current goal. Or memories, often traumatic, that you have not been able to integrate</p>
<p begin="00:05:17.890" end="00:05:21.500" style="s2"> in your consciousness.</p>
<p begin="00:05:21.500" end="00:05:27.320" style="s2"> Those nasty things take on a life of their own.</p>
<p begin="00:05:27.320" end="00:05:33.470" style="s2"> If you take an animal, and you take away bigger and bigger parts of its cortex,</p>
<p begin="00:05:33.470" end="00:05:37.780" style="s2"> that animal still continues to function like that animal.</p>
<p begin="00:05:37.780" end="00:05:41.820" style="s2"> It starts to lose function, especially if you go deep into the brain, and it can</p>
<p begin="00:05:41.820" end="00:05:46.181" style="s2"> die if you go deep, but if you stay on the surface of the cortex</p>
<p begin="00:05:46.181" end="00:05:51.270" style="s2"> you can remove a lot of brain tissue without its ability to function</p>
<p begin="00:05:51.270" end="00:05:53.000" style="s2"> strongly disrupt.</p>
<p begin="00:05:53.000" end="00:05:58.610" style="s2"> That shows that the brain is organized in such a way that it has isolated parts</p>
<p begin="00:05:58.610" end="00:06:02.100" style="s2"> can act as a full personality.</p>
<p begin="00:06:02.100" end="00:06:09.390" style="s2"> That demonstrates, in a sense, that the parts of the psyche,</p>
<p begin="00:06:09.390" end="00:06:14.500" style="s2"> or the subsystems of the brain can organize themselves as functional living units.</p>
<p begin="00:06:14.500" end="00:06:16.300" style="s2"> That is also understandable.</p>
<p begin="00:06:16.300" end="00:06:18.860" style="s2"> If you lose an arm, you don&#39;t stop functioning.</p>
<p begin="00:06:18.860" end="00:06:22.000" style="s2"> You reorganize your personality without the arm.</p>
<p begin="00:06:22.000" end="00:06:28.850" style="s2"> If you&#39;ve only been able to understand some subsystems of the potential manifestations</p>
<p begin="00:06:28.850" end="00:06:35.120" style="s2"> of your psyche, that collection will define the central personality.</p>
<p begin="00:06:35.120" end="00:06:38.011" style="s2"> But all things you ignore or cannot integrate will have their own</p>
<p begin="00:06:38.011" end="00:06:39.040" style="s2"> live life.</p>
<p begin="00:06:39.040" end="00:06:41.730" style="s2"> They don&#39;t just disappear.</p>
<p begin="00:06:41.730" end="00:06:49.270" style="s2"> So Freud has the disturbing idea that you are not in charge of your own house.</p>
<p begin="00:06:49.270" end="00:06:53.060" style="s2"> You can notice that by seeing how you do things</p>
<p begin="00:06:53.060" end="00:06:55.950" style="s2"> you don&#39;t want to do.</p>
<p begin="00:06:55.950" end="00:06:59.610" style="s2"> For example things you don&#39;t want to be confronted with,</p>
<p begin="00:06:59.610" end="00:07:03.880" style="s2"> &#39;Cause many of the things you don&#39;t want to do are things you&#39;re ashamed of</p>
<p begin="00:07:03.880" end="00:07:05.120" style="s2"> or that make you tense.</p>
<p begin="00:07:05.120" end="00:07:10.370" style="s2"> And then there is the defeat you undergo, if your ego is hypothetical</p>
<p begin="00:07:10.370" end="00:07:15.770" style="s2"> control the situation, but you discover that your behavior or thoughts are focused on something,</p>
<p begin="00:07:15.770" end="00:07:21.450" style="s2"> determined by something you thought you had under control.</p>
<p begin="00:07:21.450" end="00:07:24.130" style="s2"> You can see this clearly in conditions such as anorexia.</p>
<p begin="00:07:24.130" end="00:07:28.650" style="s2"> Especially when accompanied by bulimia, which is often the case.</p>
<p begin="00:07:28.650" end="00:07:34.270" style="s2"> Anorexia is an eating disorder that causes people to take an extreme</p>
<p begin="00:07:34.270" end="00:07:38.580" style="s2"> experience disgust for their own body.</p>
<p begin="00:07:38.580" end="00:07:40.900" style="s2"> And that disturbs their perception very much.</p>
<p begin="00:07:40.900" end="00:07:50.520" style="s2"> I had a client with anorexia at one point, a pretty short woman, maybe six feet.</p>
<p begin="00:07:50.520" end="00:07:51.780" style="s2"> Something like that.</p>
<p begin="00:07:51.780" end="00:07:54.860" style="s2"> Pretty thin, of course, she had anorexia.</p>
<p begin="00:07:54.860" end="00:08:00.400" style="s2"> When she was in my office, I asked if her thigh was wider or narrower than mine.</p>
<p begin="00:08:00.400" end="00:08:03.110" style="s2"> She said they were similar.</p>
<p begin="00:08:03.110" end="00:08:09.930" style="s2"> So I took a piece of paper, sat on it, and marked the size of my thigh.</p>
<p begin="00:08:09.930" end="00:08:14.050" style="s2"> And then I let her sit on the same piece of paper, and she drew the size of her thigh.</p>
<p begin="00:08:14.050" end="00:08:18.220" style="s2"> And of course there was about that much space in between on both sides.</p>
<p begin="00:08:18.220" end="00:08:21.360" style="s2"> She watched it for fifteen minutes.</p>
<p begin="00:08:21.360" end="00:08:26.140" style="s2"> She couldn&#39;t believe that it was.</p>
<p begin="00:08:26.140" end="00:08:31.350" style="s2"> I think anorexic patients can no longer see their whole body.</p>
<p begin="00:08:31.350" end="00:08:32.350" style="s2"></p>
<p begin="00:08:32.350" end="00:08:38.140" style="s2"> If you look at yourself in the mirror, you have to form a &quot;Gestalt&quot;, as it were,</p>
<p begin="00:08:38.140" end="00:08:40.970" style="s2"> form an overall picture.</p>
<p begin="00:08:40.970" end="00:08:45.280" style="s2"> You can also focus on small parts, but the more you concentrate on parts,</p>
<p begin="00:08:45.280" end="00:08:49.140" style="s2"> the more difficult it is to see the parts in relation to the whole.</p>
<p begin="00:08:49.140" end="00:08:54.930" style="s2"> And anorexic patients fixate on small parts and confuse themselves.</p>
<p begin="00:08:54.930" end="00:09:01.910" style="s2"> For example, if they look at their arm and it has flesh on it,</p>
<p begin="00:09:01.910" end="00:09:06.560" style="s2"> they cannot distinguish between meat and fat. And they don&#39;t want fat, they want</p>
<p begin="00:09:06.560" end="00:09:08.000" style="s2"> just blunt.</p>
<p begin="00:09:08.000" end="00:09:12.810" style="s2"> Because they are concerned about this small part, or</p>
<p begin="00:09:12.810" end="00:09:17.560" style="s2"> this little part, or whatever they focus on, they lose the ability</p>
<p begin="00:09:17.560" end="00:09:18.960" style="s2"> to perceive their body.</p>
<p begin="00:09:18.960" end="00:09:22.880" style="s2"> And it&#39;s amazing how far that can go.</p>
<p begin="00:09:22.880" end="00:09:29.690" style="s2"> And with bulimia, someone starves themselves for a long time.</p>
<p begin="00:09:29.690" end="00:09:35.870" style="s2"> We will look at this from modern physiology.</p>
<p begin="00:09:35.870" end="00:09:40.560" style="s2"> Eating behavior is regulated by the hypothalamus, which is a very old part of the brain</p>
<p begin="00:09:40.560" end="00:09:43.000" style="s2"> that drives fundamental motivation systems.</p>
<p begin="00:09:43.000" end="00:09:47.140" style="s2"> It&#39;s just above the spinal cord, and it&#39;s a very strong control center</p>
<p begin="00:09:47.140" end="00:09:49.130" style="s2"> in the brain.</p>
<p begin="00:09:49.130" end="00:09:52.850" style="s2"> It functions enough to ... I think I&#39;ve mentioned this before, that if you have a cat,</p>
<p begin="00:09:52.850" end="00:09:57.080" style="s2"> and you remove her entire cortex, and even most of the emotional systems,</p>
<p begin="00:09:57.080" end="00:10:01.930" style="s2"> if you leave the hypothalamus and spinal cord in place, which means she has almost no brain,</p>
<p begin="00:10:01.930" end="00:10:06.450" style="s2"> then she can behave normally as long as you keep her in a simple environment.</p>
<p begin="00:10:06.450" end="00:10:14.710" style="s2"> So the anorexic is trying to starve himself, that&#39;s a conscious goal,</p>
<p begin="00:10:14.710" end="00:10:20.200" style="s2"> or a goal connected to her ego, you may even see it as a goal that is motivated</p>
<p begin="00:10:20.200" end="00:10:26.550" style="s2"> by unconscious forces, because she may not know why she wants to starve herself.</p>
<p begin="00:10:26.550" end="00:10:33.620" style="s2"> But what usually happens is that she comes across a situation that upsets her ...</p>
<p begin="00:10:33.620" end="00:10:39.460" style="s2"> Being emotionally upset makes you tense or hurts you.</p>
<p begin="00:10:39.460" end="00:10:43.550" style="s2"> That activates brain areas that are higher than the hypothalamus, but nevertheless quite low,</p>
<p begin="00:10:43.550" end="00:10:45.620" style="s2"> they are quite primitive.</p>
<p begin="00:10:45.620" end="00:10:50.280" style="s2"> And what does such emotional upset let&#39;s call it stress,</p>
<p begin="00:10:50.280" end="00:10:52.450" style="s2"> is turning off long-term planning.</p>
<p begin="00:10:52.450" end="00:10:58.590" style="s2"> Because when you&#39;re stressed in the present moment, your body and brain assume</p>
<p begin="00:10:58.590" end="00:11:04.120" style="s2"> that you must use the energy for the hypothetical future</p>
<p begin="00:11:04.120" end="00:11:08.720" style="s2"> to solve the current problem. And that is often a more behavioral one</p>
<p begin="00:11:08.720" end="00:11:13.120" style="s2"> solution, such as stiffening, retracting, or the like.</p>
<p begin="00:11:13.120" end="00:11:14.640" style="s2"> So it shuts down your prefrontal cortex.</p>
<p begin="00:11:14.640" end="00:11:20.590" style="s2"> When that happens, the hypothalamus, a very strong system,</p>
<p begin="00:11:20.590" end="00:11:24.480" style="s2"> in action, and dominates the person.</p>
<p begin="00:11:24.480" end="00:11:29.180" style="s2"> It&#39;s been around for tens of millions of years,</p>
<p begin="00:11:29.180" end="00:11:32.630" style="s2"> and his job is to keep you from starving.</p>
<p begin="00:11:32.630" end="00:11:36.630" style="s2"> And you can imagine someone in the course of evolution</p>
<p begin="00:11:36.630" end="00:11:41.030" style="s2"> who had a relatively weak urge to eat died.</p>
<p begin="00:11:41.030" end="00:11:43.810" style="s2"> Those were not our ancestors.</p>
<p begin="00:11:43.810" end="00:11:48.970" style="s2"> What happens to a bulimic patient is she gets upset by something, and then</p>
<p begin="00:11:48.970" end="00:11:53.840" style="s2"> gets an uncontrollable craving for something very high in calories, sweet and fat,</p>
<p begin="00:11:53.840" end="00:11:57.620" style="s2"> makes sense, given that she&#39;s starving. And then she eats a bowl of ice cream</p>
<p begin="00:11:57.620" end="00:11:59.630" style="s2"> and two loaves of bread.</p>
<p begin="00:11:59.630" end="00:12:02.840" style="s2"> And they describe the state they are in when they do so</p>
<p begin="00:12:02.840" end="00:12:04.330" style="s2"> as dissociated.</p>
<p begin="00:12:04.330" end="00:12:06.790" style="s2"> It feels like they are not themselves.</p>
<p begin="00:12:06.790" end="00:12:08.970" style="s2"> You can imagine why.</p>
<p begin="00:12:08.970" end="00:12:12.840" style="s2"> It is the whole domain of eating behavior.</p>
<p begin="00:12:12.840" end="00:12:18.170" style="s2"> And food is a sub-personality, it&#39;s not just behavior or a drive.</p>
<p begin="00:12:18.170" end="00:12:24.750" style="s2"> When you think about hunger, it&#39;s not like your brain is literally you</p>
<p begin="00:12:24.750" end="00:12:26.550" style="s2"> send determined.</p>
<p begin="00:12:26.550" end="00:12:30.470" style="s2"> You start to fantasize about food, you start to think about what you like,</p>
<p begin="00:12:30.470" end="00:12:34.520" style="s2"> and then you start making plans where to go or what to make</p>
<p begin="00:12:34.520" end="00:12:39.060" style="s2"> the social environment, and all kinds of things.</p>
<p begin="00:12:39.060" end="00:12:42.540" style="s2"> And that&#39;s the hungry &quot;you.&quot;</p>
<p begin="00:12:42.540" end="00:12:48.960" style="s2"> In an anorexia or bulimics patient, the hungry part of the person is so dissociated</p>
<p begin="00:12:48.960" end="00:12:52.340" style="s2"> of the ego, that it is in fact a war.</p>
<p begin="00:12:52.340" end="00:12:56.840" style="s2"> But one of the problems with fighting your hypothalamus is that the hypothalamus almost always wins.</p>
<p begin="00:12:56.840" end="00:12:57.840" style="s2"></p>
<p begin="00:12:57.840" end="00:12:59.960" style="s2"> And that&#39;s a good thing, because otherwise you would die.</p>
<p begin="00:12:59.960" end="00:13:03.590" style="s2"> And many anorexic patients manage to starve themselves to death.</p>
<p begin="00:13:03.590" end="00:13:08.670" style="s2"> That&#39;s a good example of how strongly the mind can dissociate.</p>
<p begin="00:13:08.670" end="00:13:13.980" style="s2"> The brain can dissociate in very strange ways.</p>
<p begin="00:13:13.980" end="00:13:15.820" style="s2"> An example.</p>
<p begin="00:13:15.820" end="00:13:20.820" style="s2"> I don&#39;t remember the name of this syndrome, maybe it still comes to mind.</p>
<p begin="00:13:20.820" end="00:13:26.860" style="s2"> You can have a particular stroke, and these are the effects of it.</p>
<p begin="00:13:26.860" end="00:13:37.020" style="s2"> You develop the delusion that someone close to you ... Capgras syndrome ... has died</p>
