<p begin="01:08:30.720" end="01:08:35.750" style="s2"> &quot;How do you know if your dream interpretation is correct?&quot; The answer is:</p>
<p begin="01:08:35.750" end="01:08:42.580" style="s2"> how do you know if you have correctly interpreted the last book you read? You do not know,</p>
<p begin="01:08:42.580" end="01:08:47.700" style="s2"> and if you did, you don&#39;t know how.</p>
<p begin="01:08:47.700" end="01:08:51.560" style="s2"> Because many people can read a book and interpret it somewhat differently.</p>
<p begin="01:08:51.560" end="01:08:56.850" style="s2"> You can consider the book as a layered pattern.</p>
<p begin="01:08:56.850" end="01:09:00.940" style="s2"> And the reader too is a layered pattern. And when you put the two together</p>
<p begin="01:09:00.940" end="01:09:05.190" style="s2"> you get a layered pattern made up of the reader and the book, and you will</p>
<p begin="01:09:05.190" end="01:09:10.400" style="s2"> are unique with every reader. But we also have common structures</p>
<p begin="01:09:10.400" end="01:09:15.251" style="s2"> through which we can communicate about it. So you read the book and it hits you</p>
<p begin="01:09:15.251" end="01:09:18.670" style="s2"> some things hit you, and some things seem right. If you interpret a dream</p>
<p begin="01:09:18.670" end="01:09:24.069" style="s2"> you work with the client on the interpretation.</p>
<p begin="01:09:24.069" end="01:09:30.600" style="s2"> What I usually do is people tell me their dream from the beginning to the end.</p>
<p begin="01:09:30.600" end="01:09:35.500" style="s2"> Freud would say you introduce all kinds of assumptions right away, because they don&#39;t tell you the dream,</p>
<p begin="01:09:35.500" end="01:09:40.359" style="s2"> they tell you the dream as they interpret and remember it.</p>
<p begin="01:09:40.359" end="01:09:44.750" style="s2"> Yes, that is a problem. But you do what you can.</p>
<p begin="01:09:44.750" end="01:09:48.530" style="s2"> I tell people, &quot;Write it down as soon as you can, without thinking too much about it.&quot;</p>
<p begin="01:09:48.530" end="01:09:54.290" style="s2"> Because we don&#39;t want any subsequent edits. Then I listen to it and they tell it</p>
<p begin="01:09:54.290" end="01:09:59.620" style="s2"> again, slowly. Then I listen to a sentence, and I let my ability to associate work,</p>
<p begin="01:09:59.620" end="01:10:04.900" style="s2"> and then I see what that reminds me of, and then I ask the person</p>
<p begin="01:10:04.900" end="01:10:09.710" style="s2"> what it reminds him of. And then we talk about that. Those are the direct associations,</p>
<p begin="01:10:09.710" end="01:10:13.920" style="s2"> the things Freud would call free associations. And you can say that</p>
<p begin="01:10:13.920" end="01:10:19.380" style="s2"> around every utterance, such as a sentence, there is a collection of potential meanings.</p>
<p begin="01:10:19.380" end="01:10:24.330" style="s2"> These can be direct meanings, strongly related to it,</p>
<p begin="01:10:24.330" end="01:10:30.030" style="s2"> and loose meanings. The client and therapist can continue to exchange thoughts</p>
<p begin="01:10:30.030" end="01:10:34.620" style="s2"> until you think, &quot;Okay, it seems to be heading that way.&quot; And you can see it too</p>
<p begin="01:10:34.620" end="01:10:39.480" style="s2"> in relation to the person&#39;s actual experiences, and the rest of the dream,</p>
<p begin="01:10:39.480" end="01:10:44.460" style="s2"> and maybe all the dreams he&#39;s told you before. So it is extremely complex.</p>
<p begin="01:10:44.460" end="01:10:48.650" style="s2"> But people also do that when they listen to a conversation. How do you know if</p>
<p begin="01:10:48.650" end="01:10:55.740" style="s2"> your interpretation of a conversation is correct? There are several ways</p>
<p begin="01:10:55.740" end="01:11:00.370" style="s2"> to approach that, but you&#39;re not sure. There are many different ways</p>
<p begin="01:11:00.370" end="01:11:05.100" style="s2"> to interpret a conversation. That&#39;s why the Postmodernists in one</p>
<p begin="01:11:05.100" end="01:11:09.810" style="s2"> black hole with regard to literature. They realized there is no limit to the amount of manners</p>
<p begin="01:11:09.810" end="01:11:14.830" style="s2"> to interpret a book. But then they took it a step further:</p>
<p begin="01:11:14.830" end="01:11:22.140" style="s2"> &quot;Therefore it has no meaning.&quot; No, incorrect. That&#39;s a simplistic way of thinking.</p>
<p begin="01:11:22.140" end="01:11:27.940" style="s2"> It means that the way the book conveys meaning is very complex,</p>
<p begin="01:11:27.940" end="01:11:32.700" style="s2"> you cannot describe it on the basis of normal, linear rationality. That&#39;s not to say there is no meaning.</p>
<p begin="01:11:32.700" end="01:11:37.650" style="s2"> That is so sad. It&#39;s such a sad theory. And it&#39;s dangerous too</p>
<p begin="01:11:37.650" end="01:11:42.130" style="s2"> for it means that nothing has meaning, and that is the most dangerous theory.</p>
<p begin="01:11:42.130" end="01:11:47.710" style="s2"> Either way, you talk to the person about the dream and the dream image, and about</p>
<p begin="01:11:47.710" end="01:11:54.020" style="s2"> what that evokes memories. And you also pay attention to what they say because sometimes ...</p>
<p begin="01:11:54.020" end="01:11:58.760" style="s2"> For example, this happened recently, someone is describing a dream</p>
<p begin="01:11:58.760" end="01:12:02.950" style="s2"> where he&#39;s walking around, and he says, &quot;I&#39;m on the wrong road.&quot;</p>
<p begin="01:12:02.950" end="01:12:06.780" style="s2"> And you think, &quot;Okay.&quot; Now we know what your dream means because</p>
<p begin="01:12:06.780" end="01:12:12.030" style="s2"> you just said it. &quot;I&#39;m on the wrong track.&quot; That&#39;s a Freudian slip of the tongue.</p>
<p begin="01:12:12.030" end="01:12:16.100" style="s2"> That&#39;s interesting because if you listen to how people tell their dreams, you have to listen to ...</p>
<p begin="01:12:16.100" end="01:12:21.300" style="s2"> it is as if they have two spirits speaking at the same time. One describes the dream,</p>
<p begin="01:12:21.300" end="01:12:25.260" style="s2"> but the other describes his life, and they don&#39;t see the connection.</p>
<p begin="01:12:25.260" end="01:12:29.030" style="s2"> And you point it out, and they say, &quot;Oh, yeah, I didn&#39;t realize I was saying that.&quot;</p>
<p begin="01:12:29.030" end="01:12:33.540" style="s2"> That&#39;s a Freudian slip of the tongue. What&#39;s happening is ... the right hemisphere of the brain</p>
<p begin="01:12:33.540" end="01:12:40.210" style="s2"> is a system that collects images, a kind of system that collects low-resolution patterns,</p>
<p begin="01:12:40.210" end="01:12:45.160" style="s2"> that mainly uses images and tries to create meaningful coherence,</p>
<p begin="01:12:45.160" end="01:12:51.270" style="s2"> but that meaning is vague and comprehensive. And the left hemisphere</p>
<p begin="01:12:51.270" end="01:12:56.500" style="s2"> the linguistic hemisphere tries to make clear what that means, but in words.</p>
<p begin="01:12:56.500" end="01:13:01.790" style="s2"> It&#39;s very difficult to make that transition, but that&#39;s why dream analysis works in part.</p>
<p begin="01:13:01.790" end="01:13:06.700" style="s2"> Because you allow the information to move from images</p>
<p begin="01:13:06.700" end="01:13:12.380" style="s2"> to the articulated part of the personality. You move information up the hierarchy of abstraction,</p>
<p begin="01:13:12.380" end="01:13:18.770" style="s2"> to the point where it can be used. I will conclude this discussion of Freud</p>
<p begin="01:13:18.770" end="01:13:25.840" style="s2"> with a description of research that has been carried out recently,</p>
<p begin="01:13:25.840" end="01:13:31.970" style="s2"> relatively recently, for the past twenty years, by a psychologist at the University of Texas,</p>
<p begin="01:13:31.970" end="01:13:38.450" style="s2"> in Austin, called James Pennebaker. And Pennebaker is a very smart psychologist.</p>
<p begin="01:13:38.450" end="01:13:43.310" style="s2"> Freud had another idea related to therapy. He thought</p>
<p begin="01:13:43.310" end="01:13:46.942" style="s2"> that if you were undergoing therapy and talked about a traumatic event,</p>
<p begin="01:13:46.942" end="01:13:53.850" style="s2"> that you were then healed by &quot;catharsis.&quot; That meant the trauma was linked to a collection of feelings,</p>
<p begin="01:13:53.850" end="01:13:57.680" style="s2"> who were oppressed, but who tried to rise from the depths,</p>
<p begin="01:13:57.680" end="01:14:01.441" style="s2"> and caused all kinds of stress and misery because you tried to stop them. And if you</p>
<p begin="01:14:01.441" end="01:14:07.590" style="s2"> talking to someone about it and expressing your feelings would help you.</p>
<p begin="01:14:07.590" end="01:14:13.540" style="s2"> Expressing your feelings doesn&#39;t help, by the way. That turns out to be wrong, but</p>
<p begin="01:14:13.540" end="01:14:17.790" style="s2"> it is wrong in an interesting and useful way. Because it is almost right.</p>
<p begin="01:14:17.790" end="01:14:24.020" style="s2"> Pennebaker dropped &quot;undergraduates&quot; for three consecutive days</p>
<p begin="01:14:24.020" end="01:14:29.490" style="s2"> come to the study, and had them write for 15 minutes every day,</p>
<p begin="01:14:29.490" end="01:14:32.941" style="s2"> about the worst thing they had ever done or experienced.</p>
<p begin="01:14:32.941" end="01:14:37.730" style="s2"> Often people are traumatized by something they&#39;ve done, not something they&#39;ve been through.</p>
<p begin="01:14:37.730" end="01:14:42.140" style="s2"> More often, because someone sees themselves doing something terrible,</p>
<p begin="01:14:42.140" end="01:14:47.650" style="s2"> and thinks, &quot;My God, that&#39;s what I did! Who am I?&quot; They have no idea</p>
<p begin="01:14:47.650" end="01:14:53.320" style="s2"> and then things start to collapse. Anyway, Pennebaker let them do that,</p>
<p begin="01:14:53.320" end="01:14:56.700" style="s2"> and for the next two weeks they were pretty miserable. That is interesting,</p>
<p begin="01:14:56.700" end="01:15:01.260" style="s2"> because if they only measured the result of that intervention in those two weeks,</p>
<p begin="01:15:01.260" end="01:15:05.850" style="s2"> everyone would have said, &quot;Never write down your traumatic experiences,</p>
<p begin="01:15:05.850" end="01:15:11.100" style="s2"> because that makes it worse. ”But in the six months after that, what happened in particular,</p>
<p begin="01:15:11.100" end="01:15:15.330" style="s2"> was that their physical health improved. They went to the doctor less, they were</p>
<p begin="01:15:15.330" end="01:15:19.180" style="s2"> less often sick, et cetera. That was because their general stress level decreased,</p>
<p begin="01:15:19.180" end="01:15:24.750" style="s2"> for complex reasons that we can talk about later. And Pennebaker, a good scientist, thought:</p>
<p begin="01:15:24.750" end="01:15:29.970" style="s2"> &quot;Okay, catharsis works.&quot; You are venting your trauma, and &quot;poof!&quot; it is solved.</p>
<p begin="01:15:29.970" end="01:15:35.120" style="s2"> But then he thought, &quot;Wait a minute, maybe it&#39;s important how you express it.&quot;</p>
<p begin="01:15:35.120" end="01:15:39.130" style="s2"> So he went back and counted all the words that had to do with emotion,</p>
<p begin="01:15:39.130" end="01:15:44.680" style="s2"> and all words related to understanding and cognition. And he discovered two things:</p>
<p begin="01:15:44.680" end="01:15:50.980" style="s2"> the more words you used, as your story developed,</p>
<p begin="01:15:50.980" end="01:15:55.810" style="s2"> that indicated insight and understanding, the better you were, in the long run.</p>
<p begin="01:15:55.810" end="01:16:01.460" style="s2"> It&#39;s not about expressing your feelings, it&#39;s about expressing</p>
<p begin="01:16:01.460" end="01:16:09.940" style="s2"> your feelings and weaving the memory into a new coherent representation,</p>
<p begin="01:16:09.940" end="01:16:15.750" style="s2"> from which you derive a moral. So what&#39;s the moral of trauma? &quot;Don&#39;t let it happen again!&quot;</p>
<p begin="01:16:15.750" end="01:16:20.620" style="s2"> That is the message. And the threat systems will keep bugging you with that,</p>
<p begin="01:16:20.620" end="01:16:25.720" style="s2"> until you fix it. &quot;How did I get into it? How do I keep it from happening in the future?&quot;</p>
<p begin="01:16:25.720" end="01:16:29.390" style="s2"> That doesn&#39;t mean it&#39;s your fault, but your fear systems aren&#39;t interested in that.</p>
<p begin="01:16:29.390" end="01:16:34.040" style="s2"> They want to prevent you from falling into the same hole.</p>
<p begin="01:16:34.040" end="01:16:37.760" style="s2"> And the only way to do that is analyze the causal relationships that brought you to that hole,</p>
<p begin="01:16:37.760" end="01:16:42.690" style="s2"> and see if you can change your behavior and attitude,</p>
<p begin="01:16:42.690" end="01:16:49.210" style="s2"> so that it no longer happens, or avoid such situations. One of the two.</p>
<p begin="01:16:49.210" end="01:16:56.640" style="s2"> The &quot;trauma alarm systems&quot; ... once you have an insightful representation,</p>
<p begin="01:16:56.640" end="01:17:01.600" style="s2"> what you are convinced of, they will leave you alone. And that can happen very quickly.</p>
<p begin="01:17:01.600" end="01:17:05.580" style="s2"> Like with nightmares. I cured people from nightmares in one session, no problem.</p>
<p begin="01:17:05.580" end="01:17:12.680" style="s2"> I ask them to conjure up the nightmare in their imagination. Maybe they are being chased.</p>
<p begin="01:17:12.680" end="01:17:18.400" style="s2"> &quot;Okay, imagine they&#39;re after you. You have to visualize it, really visualize it.</p>
<p begin="01:17:18.400" end="01:17:22.020" style="s2"> The more realistic the better. Okay, you&#39;re being chased. How do you feel?&quot;</p>
<p begin="01:17:22.020" end="01:17:27.310" style="s2"> &quot;I am very tense and scared.&quot; &quot;All right, turn around and see what is chasing you.&quot;</p>
<p begin="01:17:27.310" end="01:17:32.100" style="s2"> So they do. And then they possibly tell you what it is, but maybe</p>
<p begin="01:17:32.100" end="01:17:36.540" style="s2"> they don&#39;t even do that. And then I say, &quot;Before you go to sleep tonight, just before you fall asleep,</p>
<p begin="01:17:36.540" end="01:17:40.710" style="s2"> you are in a hypnagogic state in which images will appear, and then you do. &quot;</p>
<p begin="01:17:40.710" end="01:17:45.400" style="s2"> So they do that and &quot;poof,&quot; gone nightmare.</p>
<p begin="01:17:45.400" end="01:17:50.870" style="s2"> And that&#39;s because they reprogrammed themselves as ... not as something to be haunted,</p>
<p begin="01:17:50.870" end="01:17:55.610" style="s2"> like a prey, but like something that can turn around,</p>
<p begin="01:17:55.610" end="01:18:02.430" style="s2"> and confront what is haunting them. And that&#39;s the same motive as</p>
<p begin="01:18:02.430" end="01:18:06.770" style="s2"> the hunt for the dragon in the jungian archetypes. Face what you fear and it will heal you.</p>
<p begin="01:18:06.770" end="01:18:11.830" style="s2"> And that is one of the fundamental motives of Freudian psychoanalysis.</p>
<p begin="01:18:11.830" end="01:18:18.710" style="s2"> There is a test on Thursday. I will post representative questions on the internet</p>
<p begin="01:18:18.710" end="01:18:26.630" style="s2"> when I get home after this lecture, probably tonight. The test will take place here and will be multiple choice.</p>
<p begin="01:18:26.630" end="01:18:30.460" style="s2"> It will not be a problem to get it done on time, it is not that big.</p>
<p begin="01:18:30.460" end="01:18:36.220" style="s2"> If you have read the literature and attended the lectures, you will probably be fine. It&#39;s not an insidious test.</p>
<p begin="01:18:36.220" end="01:18:36.720" style="s2"></p>
